---
import { Code } from "astro:components";
import GuideLayout from "../../components/GuideLayout.astro";

const beam = `import gleam/io
import gleam/json
import watershed
import watershed/map_kernel.{ValueChanged}

pub fn main() {
  // Blocks until the op history has replayed locally.
  let assert Ok(doc) =
    watershed.connect(
      host: "127.0.0.1",
      port: 4000,
      tenant: "survey-co",
      document: "bench-book",
      token: token,
      user_id: "surveyor-ada",
    )

  let survey = watershed.root(doc)

  // Optimistic: applies locally now, sequences on the server.
  watershed.set(survey, "title", json.string("Mill Race — spring survey"))

  // One ordered stream of local + remote changes.
  watershed.subscribe(survey, fn(event) {
    case event {
      ValueChanged(key:, ..) -> io.println("revised: " <> key)
      _ -> Nil
    }
  })
}`;

const js = `import gleam/io
import gleam/json
import watershed_js.{WatershedConfig}

pub fn main() {
  let config =
    WatershedConfig(
      url: "ws://127.0.0.1:4000/socket/websocket?vsn=2.0.0",
      tenant: "survey-co",
      document: "bench-book",
      token: token,
      user_id: "surveyor-ada",
    )

  // Returns immediately; on_ready fires after handshake + history replay.
  let doc =
    watershed_js.connect(config, on_ready: fn(result) {
      case result {
        Ok(Nil) -> io.println("synced")
        Error(reason) -> io.println("rejected: " <> reason)
      }
    })

  let survey = watershed_js.root(doc)
}`;
---

<GuideLayout
  slug="connect"
  description="Step one of the watershed build guide: connect to a named, server-sequenced document, read its root map, and understand the optimistic-then-sequenced edit model — on both the BEAM and browser targets."
>
  <div class="g-block">
    <h2>A document is a named container of channels</h2>
    <p>
      Everything watershed synchronises lives inside a <strong>document</strong>:
      a server-sequenced container addressed by a <code>tenant</code> and a
      <code>document</code> id. Every client that connects to the same pair joins
      the same live state. Bench Book’s surveyors all open
      <code>survey-co / bench-book</code>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Connecting replays the document’s op history so you start from the current
      converged state, then keeps the connection open to stream every subsequent
      change — yours and everyone else’s — in one server-assigned order.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="g-block">
    <h2>Connect</h2>
    <p>
      watershed is BEAM-first, and the same pure core compiles to the browser.
      The two facades differ only where they must — how a connection is
      established — and are identical from <code>root</code> onward. Pick your
      target:
    </p>

    <div class="g-tabs">
      <input type="radio" name="target" id="t-beam" checked />
      <input type="radio" name="target" id="t-js" />
      <div class="g-tab-row" role="tablist" aria-label="Target">
        <label for="t-beam">BEAM · <code>watershed</code></label>
        <label for="t-js">Browser · <code>watershed_js</code></label>
      </div>
      <div class="g-tab-panels">
        <figure class="g-code g-panel g-panel-beam">
          <Code code={beam} lang="gleam" theme="css-variables" />
          <figcaption class="annot">
            src/bench_book.gleam · erlang target
          </figcaption>
        </figure>
        <figure class="g-code g-panel g-panel-js">
          <Code code={js} lang="gleam" theme="css-variables" />
          <figcaption class="annot">
            src/bench_book.gleam · javascript target
          </figcaption>
        </figure>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="g-note">
      <p>
        <strong>The one real difference.</strong> On the BEAM,
        <code>connect</code> blocks and returns <code>Result(Document, _)</code>
        once history has replayed — natural inside an OTP process. In the
        browser it returns immediately and calls <code>on_ready</code> when the
        handshake completes, because you cannot block the event loop. Step 05
        hands both patterns to Lustre as effects so you never write this glue by
        hand.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="g-block">
    <h2>Read the root, write optimistically</h2>
    <p>
      Every document has a root <code>SharedMap</code> at address
      <code>"root"</code> — reach it with <code>root(doc)</code>. It reads like
      an ordinary map: <code>set</code>, <code>get</code>, <code>subscribe</code>.
      There is no merge callback to write and no conflict handler to forget.
    </p>
    <p>
      A <code>set</code> applies to your local replica <em>immediately</em> so
      the UI never waits on the network, and is sent to the server to be
      sequenced. When the sequencer stamps it — and when other clients’ writes
      arrive — your <code>subscribe</code> handler sees them in the same
      server-assigned order every replica sees. That single ordered stream is
      the whole convergence contract; last write wins per key.
    </p>
    <p>
      Storing a plain string under <code>"title"</code> works, but you don’t want
      to sprinkle raw key strings through an app. Next we give the document a
      typed shape so the keys — and their types — are declared in one place.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="g-out">
    <span class="annot">You can now</span>
    <p>
      Open a live document from either target and read and write its root map,
      with local edits rendering instantly and converging in server order.
    </p>
  </div>
</GuideLayout>

<style>
  /* target toggle — radios styled as printed cells, like the demo picker.
     Pure CSS: the checked radio reveals its panel and inks its label. */
  .g-tabs {
    margin-top: var(--space-lg);
  }

  .g-tabs input {
    position: absolute;
    width: 1px;
    height: 1px;
    opacity: 0;
    pointer-events: none;
  }

  .g-tab-row {
    display: flex;
    gap: 0;
    border: 1px solid var(--ink);
    width: fit-content;
    max-width: 100%;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
  }

  .g-tab-row label {
    padding: 0.5rem 1rem;
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: var(--text-annot);
    color: var(--muted);
    cursor: pointer;
    user-select: none;
    transition:
      background var(--dur-feedback) var(--ease-out-quart),
      color var(--dur-feedback) var(--ease-out-quart);
  }

  .g-tab-row label:first-of-type {
    border-right: 1px solid var(--hairline);
  }

  .g-tab-row label code {
    font-size: 1em;
    color: inherit;
  }

  #t-beam:checked ~ .g-tab-row label[for="t-beam"],
  #t-js:checked ~ .g-tab-row label[for="t-js"] {
    background: var(--ink);
    color: var(--bg);
  }

  #t-beam:focus-visible ~ .g-tab-row label[for="t-beam"],
  #t-js:focus-visible ~ .g-tab-row label[for="t-js"] {
    outline: 2px solid var(--overprint);
    outline-offset: 2px;
  }

  .g-panel {
    display: none;
  }

  #t-beam:checked ~ .g-tab-panels .g-panel-beam,
  #t-js:checked ~ .g-tab-panels .g-panel-js {
    display: block;
  }
</style>
